<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-05-07T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-05-07T16:00:00-05:00" n="162" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d162">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/23846: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Consul at Torreon</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Donaldson</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-05-07T17:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">May 7,
                                            1920—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>Your May 5, noon.</p>
                            <p>You may, in cases of necessity, exercise your informal good offices
                                with local Mexican authorities in behalf Chinese citizens in your
                                district seeking protection. See Department’s circular telegram
                                September 30 last, 5 P.M.<note n="14" xml:id="d162fn14">Not printed;
                                    see note of Oct. 1, 1919, to the Chinese Chargé, <ref target="frus1919v02#pg_577"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                            Relations</hi>, 1919, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                                        p. 577</ref>.</note></p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>